Are you all right?

00:36:27.010 --> 00:36:29.380
If you're tired, please swap with another person.

00:36:29.380 --> 00:36:35.150
I will. I couldn't do anything in the past, so this time, I...

00:36:37.560 --> 00:36:39.170
I can't do it.

00:36:39.170 --> 00:36:40.840
I will guide you, Ma'am.

00:36:40.840 --> 00:36:44.010
- First, sit by the individual, and...
- I said I couldn't!

00:36:44.010 --> 00:36:46.590
That's your job!

00:36:46.590 --> 00:36:49.840
If I had actually acted in the moment...

00:36:51.900 --> 00:36:57.020
One, two, three, four, five, six, seven, eight, nine, ten.

00:36:57.020 --> 00:37:00.600
One, two, three, four, five, six, seven...

00:37:00.600 --> 00:37:03.950
Hang in there! You got this!

00:37:03.950 --> 00:37:07.100
M-My arms...

00:37:08.580 --> 00:37:12.250
I changed my mind! I'll help, too!

00:37:13.160 --> 00:37:19.030
One, two, three, four, five, six, seven, eight, nine, ten.

00:37:19.030 --> 00:37:22.010
- A-Am I doing this right?
- You have the right rhythm.

00:37:22.010 --> 00:37:24.850
- Press down with both hands
- One, two, three, four,

00:37:24.850 --> 00:37:28.220
- so his chest goes in about 5 centimeters.
- five, six, seven, eight, nine, ten.

00:37:28.220 --> 00:37:30.980
One, two, three, four, five, six,

00:37:30.980 --> 00:37:33.670
seven, eight, nine, ten.

00:37:33.670 --> 00:37:35.650
This is rough!

00:37:35.650 --> 00:37:38.910
- Hang in there! Help is on the way.
- One, two, three, four, five,

00:37:38.910 --> 00:37:41.520
six, seven, eight, nine, ten.

00:37:41.520 --> 00:37:44.090
- You've got this.
- One, two, three, four,

00:37:44.090 --> 00:37:47.390
five, six, seven, eight, nine, ten.

00:37:47.390 --> 00:37:49.310
Definitely,

00:37:50.150 --> 00:37:52.590
we will save you all!

00:37:53.240 --> 00:37:57.440
Ten. One, two, three, four, five,

00:37:57.440 --> 00:37:59.180
six, seven, eight, nine, ten.

00:37:59.180 --> 00:38:01.590
Yokohama Fire Bureau, this is Central. Come in.

00:38:01.590 --> 00:38:04.770
- Go ahead, Central.
- We've arrived in front of the cat cafe, "Tail."

00:38:04.770 --> 00:38:07.860
A piece of debris was blocking the automatic door. Commencing rescue.

00:38:07.860 --> 00:38:10.420
- Copy that, Central.
- We'll open the door right away!

00:38:10.420 --> 00:38:14.170
Please continue administering CPR until we make it in!

00:38:14.170 --> 00:38:17.410
Kasuhara, the rescue squad has arrived.

00:38:17.410 --> 00:38:19.760
The rescue squad will be opening the door shortly.

00:38:19.760 --> 00:38:22.370
- Keep it up just a bit longer!
- Right!

00:38:22.370 --> 00:38:25.700
One, two, three, four, five,

00:38:25.700 --> 00:38:29.090
six, seven, eight, nine, ten.

00:38:30.150 --> 00:38:32.370
Sir, are you all right?

00:38:32.370 --> 00:38:35.260
H-He's conscious again!

00:38:35.260 --> 00:38:36.950
Really?

00:38:36.950 --> 00:38:38.920
Is he breathing?

00:38:38.920 --> 00:38:42.090
Yes. Yes, he is!

00:38:42.090 --> 00:38:43.550
We've reached the individuals in need!

00:38:43.550 --> 00:38:45.530
Are you all right?

00:38:45.530 --> 00:38:47.470
Help has arrived!

00:38:47.470 --> 00:38:50.510
I hear them. Please heed their instructions to evacuate.

00:38:50.510 --> 00:38:52.410
You may end this call now.

00:38:52.410 --> 00:38:56.230
I understand. Thank you so much.

00:38:56.230 --> 00:38:59.440
- Thank you, Onee-san!
- Of course.

00:39:01.840 --> 00:39:03.840
- You've arrived at the hospital?
- Yes.

00:39:03.840 --> 00:39:07.590
From here, please follow the hospital staff's instructions.

00:39:07.590 --> 00:39:12.050
Yes, I will end our call now. Good day, Ma'am.

00:39:12.050 --> 00:39:13.650
Great job.

00:39:15.450 --> 00:39:19.300
The man is currently being transported to a hospital via chopper.

00:39:19.300 --> 00:39:22.050
Copy that.

00:39:30.690 --> 00:39:33.310
This is Takachiho speaking.

00:39:33.310 --> 00:39:35.010
Takachiho, it's me.

00:39:35.010 --> 00:39:37.660
Dojima-san? Where are you now?

00:39:37.660 --> 00:39:39.980
And what are you doing?

00:39:39.980 --> 00:39:44.470
Have the SR Special Forces dispatched to our common lounge.

00:39:44.470 --> 00:39:46.390
The police, too.

00:39:46.390 --> 00:39:50.910
Another one of Michise's humidifiers was planted here.

00:39:50.910 --> 00:39:55.240
- What?
- Michise's real target was the Bureau.

00:39:55.240 --> 00:39:59.040
The NBC incident at Luminus was a diversion.

00:39:59.040 --> 00:40:00.680
No way...

00:40:00.680 --> 00:40:03.640
However, I've already disabled it.

00:40:03.640 --> 00:40:05.830
No one is unwell either.

00:40:05.830 --> 00:40:08.340
As a precaution, I've had the citizens evacuated.

00:40:08.340 --> 00:40:11.150
Terribly sorry for the trouble.

00:40:11.150 --> 00:40:14.560
I understand. I'll have them sent here right away.

00:40:15.520 --> 00:40:19.770
Michise planted a humidifier in our lounge as well.

00:40:19.770 --> 00:40:23.180
Thankfully, the machine was disabled before it affected anyone.

00:40:23.180 --> 00:40:27.250
- Yogo-kun. Have the SR Special Forces dispatched here.
- Yes?

00:40:27.250 --> 00:40:29.980
- I'll contact the police myself.
- Copy that.

00:40:29.980 --> 00:40:31.690
What an absolute legend.

00:40:31.690 --> 00:40:35.790
He suspected we were the target at that point.

00:40:45.530 --> 00:40:47.750
Michise Motoko was rearrested

00:40:47.750 --> 00:40:50.460
for planting a humidifier at Yokohama Fire Bureau

00:40:50.460 --> 00:40:53.190
to release chlorine gas.

00:40:53.190 --> 00:40:56.870
A similar incident took place at Yokohama Luminus Mall...

00:40:56.870 --> 00:40:59.150
I can't believe

00:40:59.150 --> 00:41:02.080
someone would go to such lengths.

00:41:05.900 --> 00:41:08.930
Events beyond our imagination

00:41:08.930 --> 00:41:11.400
will surely happen again.

00:41:14.690 --> 00:41:19.220
But here's the thing. In our city...

00:41:19.220 --> 00:41:21.350
there are many citizens

00:41:21.350 --> 00:41:24.360
who are willing to save lives alongside us.

00:41:24.360 --> 00:41:26.800
[Dear Dispatchers working for the Yokohama Fire Bureau...]

00:41:38.110 --> 00:41:41.750
Is that the man who fell into the sea the other day?

00:41:41.750 --> 00:41:46.960
Yes. He recovered after some care in the hospital.

00:41:46.960 --> 00:41:51.310
Thank you for helping my boyfriend the other day.

00:41:51.310 --> 00:41:55.180
She was the one who helped us though.

00:41:59.200 --> 00:42:02.490
Say, Niijima-san.

00:42:04.830 --> 00:42:08.830
Even after you transfer to the paramedics...

00:42:13.080 --> 00:42:19.700
Well, we might still talk to each other over the radio,

00:42:19.700 --> 00:42:24.120
me as a dispatcher and you as a paramedic.

00:42:25.020 --> 00:42:26.470
Right.

00:42:31.610 --> 00:42:35.470
But we can chat about other things, can't we?

00:42:35.470 --> 00:42:38.040
- What?
- Like, outside of work.

00:42:38.040 --> 00:42:40.140
Just send word, and I'll make time.

00:42:40.140 --> 00:42:42.720
Really? That'd be okay with you?

00:42:42.720 --> 00:42:45.080
Why wouldn't it be?

00:42:46.310 --> 00:42:48.290
Fair point.

00:42:50.120 --> 00:42:53.970
The other day, I finally came to understand

00:42:54.710 --> 00:42:58.110
that I can't do anything alone.

00:43:01.330 --> 00:43:06.720
I can't save lives on my own.

00:43:09.500 --> 00:43:15.030
Dispatchers are the first to hear someone's cry for help.

00:43:15.030 --> 00:43:19.230
But dispatchers also have to listen

00:43:19.230 --> 00:43:22.050
to those voices who want to help.

00:43:26.500 --> 00:43:28.730
That's why we'll be okay...

00:43:29.790 --> 00:43:32.510
no matter what happens.

00:43:33.700 --> 00:43:36.140
We'll definitely be okay.

00:43:37.130 --> 00:43:39.450
And I have no doubts about that.

00:43:41.180 --> 00:43:42.870
You're right.

00:43:44.820 --> 00:43:51.140
♫ Without understanding how things are, I closed my eyes ♫

00:43:51.140 --> 00:43:54.420
What will you do now, Kaneshita-san?

00:43:56.840 --> 00:44:00.020
♫ What's the answer? ♫

00:44:00.020 --> 00:44:06.800
♫ To protect yourself from unfamiliar pain? Yet... ♫

00:44:06.800 --> 00:44:08.340
Twenty years old, yes?

00:44:08.340 --> 00:44:10.850
And you fell ill before you got on the train?

00:44:10.850 --> 00:44:14.900
Yes. I'm terrified of going to the office.
[20, female, anemia]

00:44:14.900 --> 00:44:16.830
What's your temperature now, Sir?

00:44:16.830 --> 00:44:18.950
It's 39℃.
[Male, 58, fever...]

00:44:18.950 --> 00:44:25.700
Maybe it's because I kept that flower-viewing spot all night.

00:44:25.700 --> 00:44:29.280
We won't be able to determine the cause of your illness.

00:44:29.280 --> 00:44:32.270
Spring is making itself known.

00:44:37.710 --> 00:44:42.230
"Sharp. Burning. Throbbing."

00:44:42.230 --> 00:44:48.050
In English, pain descriptors can change depending on the location of the injury.

00:44:48.830 --> 00:44:52.400
Yes, I've sent an ambulance your way.

00:44:52.400 --> 00:44:54.220
Then I will end the call on our end.

00:44:54.220 --> 00:44:55.390
[End call]

00:45:00.600 --> 00:45:04.760
Fire department's 119. Is it a fire or medical emergency?

00:45:04.760 --> 00:45:09.070
I understand. And where should I send the ambulance?

00:45:11.390 --> 00:45:15.150
Fire department's 119. Is it a fire or medical emergency?

00:45:15.150 --> 00:45:22.490
[119 Emergency Call]

